    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3cbcd929_a9c00de8",
        "filename": "util/linux/memory_map.cc",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 161,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-04-14T17:51:46Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Reading /proc/pid/maps brings back an unpleasant blast from the past. I’d like you to look through https://codereview.chromium.org/18661009/ to see how tricky this can actually get. We should decide whether those problems are relevant to us here, and whether we need to do anything to mitigate them.",
      "revId": "954df0dc207b1150c5b28950786163c335ffd5bb",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4f5ef2d6_70cb6795",
        "filename": "util/linux/memory_map.cc",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 161,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-04-20T00:23:44Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "So, if a separate process is doing the reading and the target process is stopped, I think none of those problems will be problems. The comment in proc_maps_linux.h mentions there are \"subtle problems\" with fork-suspend-read, but doesn\u0027t say what they were. I\u0027ll keep an eye out.\nOtherwise, if a process is tracing itself or the target process is otherwise not entirely stopped:\n\n1. The possibility of entries being re-read when a read hits a gate VMA and then new entries are mapped.\nAs is, I don\u0027t think this is a problem. FindMapping will return the first one, but either should do, assuming they are the same. MemoryMap does not expose the total number of mappings so having duplicates should be hidden for now. This will be further mediated when we convert to using a RangeMap where we can easily check if the new mapping overlaps with an existing region and whether they are identical so we can act appropriately. (We could also do this now, but seems not super important if we\u0027re going to change to a RangeMap soon anyway.)\n\n2. The comment in proc_maps_linux.h mentions the possibility of skipping entries if the virtual memory table is changed between reads, but I couldn\u0027t find an explanation of why or which entries are skipped. If this refers to any new entries added while reading, that seems like a non-problem. If entries can be added while we are reading the file, they could also be added after reading the file, even if we read it atomically.\n\n3. The possibility of an infinite (until we run out of memory and crash) loop where a new entry is added after reading a gate VMA resulting in re-reading the gate VMA, rather than hitting EOF. This seems exceedingly unlikely short of systematic allocations we while reading the file. I can think about this some more and maybe try to write a test to see if I can induce it or other badness.\n\nI think I\u0027ll start with a test on large maps files.",
      "parentUuid": "3cbcd929_a9c00de8",
      "revId": "954df0dc207b1150c5b28950786163c335ffd5bb",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
