    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "89584305_b993cfe9",
        "filename": "util/linux/memory_map_test.cc",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 146,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-04-20T00:23:44Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027ve started writing tests with the child process reading the parent since I think that\u0027s what will need to happen in practice if we fork a handler during a crash. Threads aren\u0027t preserved across a fork so the parent of a fork wouldn\u0027t be able to trace any of the non-forking threads in the child. I did read that a PTRACE_ATTACH makes the attaching process behave effectively as the parent process, but I wasn\u0027t sure how widely that held true and I don\u0027t necessarily know that the handler will be ptrace attached  when this class is used.",
      "parentUuid": "bf7b02a6_bffd4f4e",
      "revId": "954df0dc207b1150c5b28950786163c335ffd5bb",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "94709635_ccd667c6",
        "filename": "util/linux/memory_map_test.cc",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 146,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-04-20T14:50:44Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e I\u0027ve started writing tests with the child process reading the parent since I think that\u0027s what will need to happen in practice if we fork a handler during a crash.\n\nI think that we should deal with testing child-tracing-parent when we’re a level higher and are working on that actual implementation. When we get to that point, I still don’t think that we should be doing ptrace() on the test process itself, we’ll need to have distinct tracee and tracer processes.\n\n\u003e Threads aren\u0027t preserved across a fork so the parent of a fork wouldn\u0027t be able to trace any of the non-forking threads in the child.\n\nRight, we’d need the child to create its own threads. That mimics what we have to do on other operating systems.\n\nI have several concerns about child-traces-parent where the parent is a test process. Fundamentally, we’re unit testing the reader code. It’s hard to debug a test when that code’s running in a forked short-lived child process. For that matter, having a debugger attached to the test process will probably prevent the child from being able to ptrace() its parent, so this design effectively prevents a debugger from being used on the test process.\n\nThe test process is multi-purpose, and we really want to avoid doing things to it that might compromise future tests. Doing a ptrace() on it should be avoided.",
      "parentUuid": "89584305_b993cfe9",
      "revId": "954df0dc207b1150c5b28950786163c335ffd5bb",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
